{"altmetric_id":4103404,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":21,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"facebook":{"unique_users_count":4,"unique_users":["409732015727112","248898408463106","412516465495561","128791177223371"],"posts_count":5},"googleplus":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":["Utah Gastroenterology"],"posts_count":1},"news":{"unique_users_count":3,"unique_users":["medscape","healio_com","today_topics"],"posts_count":3},"total":{"posts_count":51},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":23,"unique_users":["darmtag","AETSA_","gilkaplan","AmerGastroAssn","SunnySingh1x","NEOPICS_kids","cdydev","tracilynnribble","AdipoMedCA","UtahGastro","Dr_Abdullah_Kh","StopColonCancer","endoscopic_Dr","Best_IBD_Papers","ibdtweets","A7medAlDarmaki","degboogie","fgomollon","gineblog","pakotze","LaChicaTormento","NVentham","emilyt804"],"posts_count":42}},"selected_quotes":["Meta analysis- 5 to 8 times more likely chance to die from emergency surgery as opposed to elective surgery in #ibd","What is the risk of death for #IBD surgery? video (","#IBD study coming up in Gastro","Mortality for #colitis surgery low for elective, high for emergent surgery.","Postop mortality for #IBD is not trivial Anti-TNF affect postop outcomes? see"],"citation":{"abstract":"There have been varying reports of mortality following intestinal resection for the inflammatory bowel diseases (IBD). We performed a systematic review and meta-analysis of population-based studies to determine post-operative mortality following intestinal resection in patients with IBD.\nWe searched Medline, EMBASE and PubMed, from 1990 through 2015, to identify 18 articles and 3 abstracts reporting post-operative mortality among patients with IBD. The studies included 67,057 patients with ulcerative colitis (UC) and 75,971 patients with Crohn's disease (CD), from 15 countries. Mortality estimates stratified by emergent and elective operations were separately pooled for CD and UC using a random effects model. To assess changes over time, the start year of the study was included as a continuous variable in a meta-regression model.\nIn patients with UC, post-operative mortality was significantly lower among patients who received elective (0.7%; 95% confidence interval [CI], 0.6%-0.9%]) vs emergent surgery (5.3%; 95% CI, 3.8%-7.4%]). In patients with CD, post-operative mortality was significantly lower among patients who received elective (0.6%; 95% CI, 0.2%-1.7%)] vs emergent surgery (3.6%; 95% CI, 1.8%-6.9%). Post-operative mortality did not differ for elective (p=0.78) or emergent (p=0.31) operations when patients with UC were compared to patients with CD. Post-operative mortality decreased significantly over time for patients with CD (P<.05) but not UC (P=.21).\nBased on a systematic review and meta-analysis, post-operative mortality is high following emergent, but not elective, intestinal resection in patients with UC or CD. Optimization of management strategies and more effective therapies are necessary to avoid emergent operations.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa6193cf058f6100074fe","authors":["Singh, Sunny","Al-Darmaki, Ahmed","Frolkis, Alexandra D","Seow, Cynthia H","Leung, Yvette","Novak, Kerri L","Ghosh, Subrata","Eksteen, Bertus","Panaccione, Remo","Kaplan, Gilaad G","Sunny Singh","Ahmed Al-Darmaki","Alexandra D. Frolkis","Cynthia H. Seow","Yvette Leung","Kerri L. Novak","Subrata Ghosh","Bertus Eksteen","Remo Panaccione","Gilaad G. Kaplan"],"doi":"10.1053\/j.gastro.2015.06.001","first_seen_on":"2015-06-06T04:28:14+00:00","funders":["niehs","cihr"],"issns":["0016-5085","1528-0012","00165085"],"journal":"Gastroenterology","last_mentioned_on":1499838255,"links":["http:\/\/www.gastrojournal.org\/article\/S0016-5085(15)00785-4\/abstract?rss=yes&utm_source=twitterfeed&utm_medium=facebook","http:\/\/www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\/pubmed\/26055136","http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.1053\/j.gastro.2015.06.001","http:\/\/www.sciencedirect.com\/science\/article\/pii\/S0016508515007854","http:\/\/www.gastrojournal.org\/article\/S00